HEADWORD: Falchion
<hw>Fal"chion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>fauchon</ets>, OF. <ets>fauchon</ets>, LL. <ets>f⟦aum⟧lcio</ets>,
fr. L. <ets>falx</ets>, <ets>falcis</ets>, a sickle, cf. Gr.
<?/<?/<?/<?/<?/<?/ a ship's rib, <?/<?/<?/<?/<?/<?/ bandy-legged; perh,
akin to E. <ets>falcon</ets>; cf. It. <ets>falcione</ets>. Cf.
<er>Defalcation</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A broad-bladed sword,
slightly curved, shorter and lighter than the ordinary sword; -- used in
the Middle Ages.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A name given generally and poetically to a sword,
especially to the swords of Oriental and fabled warriors.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Falcidian</ent>⟦br⟧
